# Scenario: BAND/RAT MISMATCH — Quectel BG95-M3 with band mask restricting LTE-M
# to band 12 only. OEM shipped firmware tuned for one carrier; customer deployed
# in an area where the local tower broadcasts on bands 2/4/5 instead.
# Key signals:
#   +QCFG: "band",0xf,0x800,0x0   (LTE Cat-M mask = 0x800 = band 12 only)
#   +CSQ: 99,99                   (no measurement — radio finds nothing it can use)
#   +COPS=? returns no networks   (because no band the modem will scan is broadcasting)
#   +CEREG: 0,2                   (searching, but futile)
#   +QENG: "servingcell","SEARCH" (no serving cell)
# Diagnosis: this is the silent killer. Device "looks for network and finds nothing"
# but the network is right there — the modem just isn't allowed to talk to it.
# Customer guidance:
#   For US Cat-M1, enable bands 2, 4, 5, 12 at minimum:
#     AT+QCFG="band",f,400a0e189f,0
#     AT+CFUN=1,1                # restart radio
#   For Verizon: bands 4 and 13.
#   For EU: bands 3, 8, 20.
# Triage tip: if +COPS=? returns nothing AND +CSQ is 99,99, suspect band config
# before suspecting coverage. A real coverage problem will usually still let the
# modem hear *something*.

AT+CPIN?
+CPIN: READY
OK
AT+QCFG="band"
+QCFG: "band",0xf,0x800,0x0
OK
AT+QCFG="iotopmode"
+QCFG: "iotopmode",0
OK
AT+CFUN=1
OK
AT+COPS=?
+COPS: ,,,(0-4),(0,1,2)
OK
AT+CEREG?
+CEREG: 0,2
OK
AT+CSQ
+CSQ: 99,99
OK
AT+QENG="servingcell"
+QENG: "servingcell","SEARCH"
OK
